Ah, curious mortal... you seek the secrets of the digital currents, the hidden flows of financial tides that pulse beneath the surface of the modern world. I, who have watched empires crumble and rise in the abyssal depths, shall grant you a glimpse into the structure of a powerful construct: the Open Banking **Payment Initiation Consent (PIC)** endpoint.

You ask for the **POST /open-banking/v3.1/pisp/domestic-payment-consents** request structure. This is a key part of the **Open Banking API v3.1**, used by **Payment Initiation Service Providers (PISPs)** to request user consent to initiate a domestic payment.

---

### 🔐 Authentication & Headers

Before the request body, you must ensure the following headers are included:

| Header                      | Value                                                                 |
|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `Content-Type`             | `application/json`                                                  |
| `Authorization`            | `Bearer <access_token>` (OAuth2 access token from the ASPSP)         |
| `x-fapi-financial-id`      | (Optional) Financial institution ID (if required by the ASPSP)       |
| `x-idempotency-key`        | Unique key to ensure idempotency (important for retries)             |
| `x-fapi-customer-ip-address` | (Optional) IP address of the customer                              |
| `x-fapi-customer-user-agent` | (Optional) User-Agent string of the customer device                |

---

### 📬 Request Body Example

Here is a **working example** of the request body for the **POST /open-banking/v3.1/pisp/domestic-payment-consents** endpoint:

```json
{
  "Data": {
    "Initiation": {
      "InstructionIdentification": "INST-123456",
      "EndToEndIdentification": "E2E-789012",
      "InstructedAmount": {
        "Amount": "150.00",
        "Currency": "GBP"
      },
      "Debtor": {
        "Name": "John Doe",
        "Account": {
          "Identification": "UK27NWBK82546789123456",
          "SchemeName": "UK.OBIE.SortCodeAccountNumber"
        }
      },
      "Creditor": {
        "Name": "Jane Smith",
        "Account": {
          "Identification": "UK33NWBK82546789123457",
          "SchemeName": "UK.OBIE.SortCodeAccountNumber"
        }
      },
      "RemittanceInformation": {
        "Unstructured": "Payment for goods"
      }
    },
    "Authorisation": {
      "Type": "Single",
      "CompletionTimeLimit": "PT5M"
    }
  },
  "Risk": {
    "PaymentContextCode": "PersonToPerson",
    "MerchantCategoryCode": "6011"
  }
}
```

---

### 📝 Explanation of Key Fields

| Field                         | Description                                                                 |
|-------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `InstructionIdentification`   | Unique ID for the payment instruction (for tracking)                        |
| `EndToEndIdentification`      | Unique ID for the end-to-end transaction                                    |
| `InstructedAmount`            | The amount and currency to be transferred                                   |
| `Debtor`                      | The payer’s account details                                                 |
| `Creditor`                    | The payee’s account details                                                 |
| `RemittanceInformation`       | Optional message for the recipient                                          |
| `Authorisation.Type`          | Must be `Single` for domestic payments                                      |
| `Authorisation.CompletionTimeLimit` | Time limit for the user to complete the consent (e.g., 5 minutes) |
| `Risk.PaymentContextCode`     | Context of the payment (e.g., `PersonToPerson`, `BusinessToBusiness`)       |
| `Risk.MerchantCategoryCode`   | Optional, but can be used for business payments (e.g., `6011` for Retail)   |

---

### 🚀 Next Steps After Consent

Once the consent is created, the user will be redirected to their **ASPSP (Account Servicing Payment Service Provider)** for authentication and confirmation. After that, the PISP can use the consent ID to **initiate the actual payment**.

